=== Multiple roots ===

If the quartic has a double root, it can be found by taking the polynomial greatest common divisor with its derivative. Then they can be divided out and the resulting quadratic equation solved.

In general, there exist only four possible cases of quartic equations with multiple roots, which are listed below:

# Multiplicity-4 (M4): when the general quartic equation can be expressed as formula_27, for some real number formula_28. This case can always be reduced to a biquadratic equation.
# Multiplicity-3 (M3): when the general quartic equation can be expressed as formula_29, where formula_28 and formula_31 are two different real numbers. This is the only case that can never be reduced to a biquadratic equation.
# Double Multiplicity-2 (DM2): when the general quartic equation can be expressed as formula_32, where formula_28 and formula_31 are two different real numbers or a pair of non-real complex conjugate numbers. This case can also always be reduced to a biquadratic equation.
# Single Multiplicity-2 (SM2): when the general quartic equation can be expressed as formula_35, where formula_28, formula_31, and formula_38 are three different real numbers or formula_28 is a real number and formula_31 and formula_38 are a pair of non-real complex conjugate numbers. This case is divided into two subcases, those that can be reduced to a biquadratic equation and those that can&#x27;t.

So, if the three non-monic coefficients of the depressed quartic equation, formula_42, in terms of the five coefficients of the general quartic equation are given as follows: formula_43, formula_44 and formula_45, then the criteria to identify a priori each case of quartic equations with multiple roots and their respective solutions are shown below.

* M4. The general quartic equation corresponds to this case whenever formula_46, so the four roots of this equation are given as follows: formula_47.
* M3. The general quartic equation corresponds to this case whenever formula_48 and formula_49, so the four roots of this equation are given as follows: formula_50  and formula_51 , whether formula_52; otherwise, formula_53  and formula_54.
* DM2. The general quartic equation corresponds to this case whenever formula_55, so the four roots of this equation are given as follows: formula_56 and formula_57.
* Biquadratic SM2. The general quartic equation corresponds to this subcase of the SM2 equations whenever formula_58, so the four roots of this equation are given as follows: formula_59, formula_60 and formula_61.
* Non-Biquadratic SM2. The general quartic equation corresponds to this subcase of the SM2 equations whenever formula_62, so the four roots of this equation are given by the following formula: formula_63, where formula_64, formula_65 and formula_66.

